g.text: EleanorRank4Convo5 begins.

g.title: j3663569521
g.text: The Kingdom you used to rule over. Duviri. You didn’t invent it, did you?

g.title: j2050921471
g.text: I did and I didn’t. The place and the characters came from a children’s book I used to love. ‘Tales of Duviri’. I brought it to life through the Void.

g.title: j3374209503
g.text: I am so sick of talking about Duviri...

g.title: j1994111704
g.text: However did you achieve that?

g.title: j3438048709
g.text: +5 Chemistry

g.title: j147091660
g.text: I was all alone. I guess the other kids were dead, or rescued. I’m kind of hazy on the details.

g.title: j2229920454
g.text: It wasn’t exactly intentional. All I remember is…

g.title: j1049043502
g.text: Oops. My mistake.

g.title: j1576207060
g.text: The Angels were coming, breaking through the walls, and I had nowhere to run. I had the book, then I just remember thinking ‘This is where I can be safe.’

g.title: j2534748574
g.text: That was thoughtless of me, wasn't it? The place wasn't exactly a holiday camp for you.

g.title: j3480197315
g.text: Angels? In this time, angels are thought of as benevolent creatures. Terrifying, sometimes, but on the side of good. Unless you mean the fallen ones.

g.title: j2234091484
g.text: I'm sincerely sorry. I'll keep my curiosity under control from now on.

g.title: j894267987
g.text: That hasn’t really changed in my time. Angels are meant to be winged, shining creatures from the old stories who help good humans. I’m talking about Void Angels. They’re a whole different beast.

g.title: Chat ends.
g.text: Chat ends.

g.title: j1174311836
g.text: I see. I can’t imagine something called a ‘Void Angel’ swooping down and blessing a newborn babe.

g.title: j1252266073
g.text: So far as I can make out, they used to be people. When the Angels’ song reaches them, they start to change. Once they can’t resist it any more, they become Angels themselves.

g.title: j3083976904
g.text: The future, as you describe it, sounds bloody horrible.

g.title: j22309887
g.text: I can’t blame you for wanting to hide away from these Void Angels. Especially if they were…

g.title: j3812454451
g.text: Oh. I just got a feeling. They weren’t your parents, were they?

g.title: j968591257
g.text: I’m fairly certain my parents are dead.

g.title: j1916672728
g.text: They could have been. Other kids heard their parents calling.

g.title: j1340992549
g.text: I think they were, yeah. Quinn warned me not to look for familiar voices. That must have been what he meant.

g.title: j4219487412
g.text: I’m so sorry. I’m glad you found safe harbour, even if it didn’t stay that way.

g.title: j2044221012
g.text: It was safe for a long time. Long enough for me to forget. I guess that’s what I wanted to do.

g.title: j1091908430
g.text: But how on earth did you do it? You were only a child. What gave you the power to conjure an entire kingdom out of nothing?

g.title: j689174268
g.text: Children are fascinating in the fact that they don't know what they can't do yet. I didn't know I couldn't. So I did.

g.title: j1760140091
g.text: I had so many emotions, all at once, that I... just... did something with them. It's hard to explain.

g.title: j2068972553
g.text: The Void isn’t ‘nothing’. I know it sounds like it should be, but it’s not. Albrecht proved that.

g.title: j2134253012
g.text: When I was five, I wanted to be a witch. I yelled Abracadabra and jumped from the top of the stairs. I didn't know I couldn't fly. But I quickly found out.

g.title: j4032901519
g.text: We know very little about it, even now. But one thing even the Orokin figured out is this: the Void responds to human emotions.

g.title: j2187801207
g.text: The power to create Duviri must have come from somewhere other than you. You used it to do something incredible, but it wasn't yours.

g.title: j3490152609
g.text: I SEE. So if you looked into the Void with… hmm, let’s say ‘hunger’… you might create a prowling half-starved wolf. Or a royal banquet, maybe. Or a loaf of bread with wolf’s teeth gnashing in it.

g.title: j2512395102
g.text: Not at first, anyway. It's in you now, though. The wild energy. The loops in time. Gods, you're a wonder.

g.title: j685350802
g.text: What a terrifying, exhilarating thought.

g.title: j4065454588
g.text: Whyever did the Orokin think it was a good idea to launch a ship full of children into the Void? Wasn’t that an emotional time bomb waiting to go off?

g.title: j1166106999
g.text: That’s what that book of stories was meant to be for. On the surface it was all about these over-the-top characters in the court of a mad King who changed his moods every day.

g.title: j3051691184
g.text: But the real lesson of the stories was about how to rule over your emotions. We were meant to learn an important lesson from it, so the voyage would be safe.

g.title: j354658320
g.text: Ugh. Sorry, but you’ve ruined it for me now.

g.title: j3245958670
g.text: Why can’t stories just be stories? I HATED it when I found out that Rudolfo the Leopard King who died heroically in battle with the Zodiac Serpent was meant to be Sol with his sun-spots, suffering on the star-tree.

g.title: j828687649
g.text: Smuggling religion into kids’ books is like hiding medicine inside sweeties. JUST TELL THEM.

g.title: j1442460607
g.text: I’ve never heard of Rudolfo the Leopard King.

g.title: j2919300462
g.text: I want to hear the story of Rudolfo the Leopard King someday.

g.title: j364243705
g.text: I can die a happy woman knowing that those books get forgotten about. Hurrah for the future!

g.title: j3063018256
g.text: Ugh. Please, no. It's not a real legend, it's a terrible series of children's books.

g.title: j2409656171
g.text: You do have stories, though, don’t you?

g.title: j2730376997
g.text: I could tell you some of our real legends, though, if you like.

g.title: j2116151196
g.text: Plenty. Even the Tenno and the Warframes have stories.

g.title: j3582517816
g.text: I'd like that.

g.title: j4145962452
g.text: Not right now. [End.]

g.title: j2450690832
g.text: There’s this guy, Drusus Leverian. He’s like a museum curator. He keeps records of all the legends of the Warframes.

g.title: j3701175688
g.text: Let’s see. There’s Arthur, of course. Good old Arthur. The original. Britannia’s finest.

g.title: j613455495
g.text: Well, that’s boggled my noggin. You’re from the far future, but you’ve also been out of the loop in Duviri for so many years that events that happened in your lifetime have had time to become myths?

g.title: j3899084297
g.text: Then there’s Young Loxley. I loved her. Wanted to be her. She was the model for a certain kind of young woman.

g.title: j725838099
g.text: I’m getting vertigo.

g.title: j1325072695
g.text: What’s her story?

g.title: j2646130313
g.text: Trust me. I know how you feel.

g.title: j922585423
g.text: Tell me about your myths, then.

g.title: j1513310352
g.text: Okay. Potted version: she was the daughter of a nobleman back in ye olde days, when the land was suffering under a cruel King.

g.title: j2808469540
g.text: You're a storybook character yourself, aren't you?

g.title: j2154743673
g.text: Blimey. We’ll be here all year if I start.

g.title: j2611033618
g.text: Her brother had been killed off fighting in foreign climes, but word hadn’t reached home yet, so when the poor oppressed people needed a hero she rose to the occasion.

g.title: j4182824444
g.text: Trapped in a magical kingdom where time flows differently, summoned to the place where you were most needed...

g.title: j1630342508
g.text: Check boolean EleanorHeroVirus

g.title: j3126994951
g.text: All we need to round your story off is a love interest, or a slavering, inhuman monster.

g.title: j271119886
g.text: I thought you hated heroes.

g.title: j1630342508->j271119886
g.text: true

g.title: j3283997186
g.text: Now, normally I can't stand hero figures. They're toxic. Infectious, and for that reason, dangerous.

g.title: j1630342508->j3283997186
g.text: false

g.title: j2015165266
g.text: (Or a slavering, inhuman love interest, depending on how your tastes run.)

g.title: j3940245318
g.text: She gets a pass. Shut up.

g.title: j216719422
g.text: Young Loxley's different.

g.title: j3941923797
g.text: I've always found the monsters more interesting, anyway. Heroes are boring. Predictable. ...Mundane.

g.title: j900392784
g.text: Mm, I'm not sure if monsters are really my type.

g.title: j2589507924
g.text: As I was saying. She looked a lot like her brother, so she dressed up in his old clothes and pretended to be him, and went off to lead a revolution. If anyone got too close they might notice she was a girl, so she took to wearing a hood. It became her trademark.

g.title: j1994938903
g.text: Boolean EleanorHeroVirus is now true.

g.title: j2443272088
g.text: Boolean EleanorFlirt is now true.

g.title: j1640018454
g.text: And that's fine, honestly.

g.title: j2851436477
g.text: She was shit-hot with a bow and arrow. She and her crew became this beloved band of outlaws, robbing from the King’s tax collectors and giving the money to whoever needed it most.

g.title: j793271945
g.text: +15 Chemistry

g.title: j1253965095
g.text: Monsters are used to being alone.

g.title: j2483739677
g.text: Sounds like she would have commanded respect in her own right. Why’d she need to pretend to be her brother?

g.title: j1644127568
g.text: Monstrosity is in the eye of the beholder, my friend.

g.title: j112651306
g.text: We're survivors.

g.title: j2644996604
g.text: That’s history for you. Back then, men supposedly did all the fighting, so they did the ruling too. People expected to take orders from men. She needed to draw on her brother’s reputation to do what she had to do. It was that or go under.

g.title: j3453311801
g.text: If you are sincerely drawn to the qualities you think 'monstrous' in another, then you had better make sure they share your choice of labels and revel in it. Otherwise, you commit the grossest fetishization.

g.title: j4155634497
g.text: What happened to her in the end?

g.title: j3992069328
g.text: I'm so glad we fixed that in the future.

g.title: j1064280435
g.text: I'm not sure we *entirely* fixed that in the future...

g.title: j313913568
g.text: Would I call myself a monster, for example? Yes. Enthusiastically. I take the title others would condemn me by, and I rejoice in it. In case you were wondering.

g.title: j79781838
g.text: +20 Chemistry

g.title: j3704169414
g.text: +20 Chemistry

g.title: j2607782357
g.text: +20 Chemistry

g.title: j3556240596
g.text: It depends which version of the story you read. She either got called straight to the Hall of Heroes, or married the King’s wayward daughter, or got trapped in an oak tree where she sleeps to this day waiting for Britannia’s hour of need.

g.title: j698266639
g.text: So am I.

g.title: j3311997449
g.text: Not if that Ballas character is anything to go by, you didn't.

g.title: j1655731968
g.text: Hence the saying back home. If things are going badly, like they were during the war, it’s tradition to shrug and say ‘Well, it can’t be THAT bad. Young Loxley’s not turned up yet.’

g.title: j1359279075
g.text: Gods, I'd love to see your era with my own eyes. Maybe you could smuggle me back one of those icebox coffin things and I can just sleeeeeep for a few millennia.

g.title: j3189677017
g.text: How much bloody longer do we need? FFS.
